{
  "answer": "**Ghalib compares the world (*duniya*) to the playthings or game of children (*baazeecha-e-atfal*) in the matla of ghazal 213 from his *Diwan*.**[^1]\n\nThis opening couplet reads in English translation: \"This world is but a **children's game**, a vast display, / Where night and day a spectacle unfolds my way.\" The term *baazeecha-e-atfal* evokes the fleeting, illusory nature of childish play or toys, a common Sufi-inspired metaphor in Urdu poetry for the transience of worldly existence.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/213-baazeecha-e-atfaal-hai-duniya-mere-aage/translation/#p-3132be).\n\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [chapter](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/213-baazeecha-e-atfaal-hai-duniya-mere-aage/translation/).",
